bio: Studying for 3D print modeler at 3D Ambacht

I have been into 3D models since I took a class a decade ago.

I first made models for digital testing of steel tubular structures in a project at school. After that I helped my wife with a couple of models for one of her projects. She is an architect, by the way. The next thing I did with 3D software was a model for each of the designs in a truck manufacturing plant I was working at the moment. The management asked about the models and decided to make a video with the models for publicity purposes.

Then I found Thingiverse, this awesome page were anyone can post 3D models of anything. I want to continue my journey with 3D design and hope there is a public out there for what I do. Hopefully, it not all just fan service and we manage to make something useful together.

If you like what I do, let me know by supporting me on Patreon https://www.patreon.com/leobb

DDR-DreiDimensionaleRevolution
Academy of 3D-Printing

Die DDR in Duisburg-Rheinhausen ist ein offenes Entwicklungslabor und Schulungszentrum mit Themenschwerpunkt 3D-Druck.

Hier können Sie Ihre Projekte und Ideen umsetzen. Lassen Sie Ihre Vorstellung Realität werden. Sie können hier umfangreiches Equipment und verfügbare Arbeitsplätze nutzen. Außerdem haben Sie Zugriff auf 3D-Drucker vom Typ Vellemann K8200 und K8400, einen CAD-Arbeitsplatz, einen 3D-Scanner (Kinect+Software) und eine Bibliothek mit Fachliteratur und Leseecke.

Sie interessieren sich für das Thema 3D-Drucken, haben aber noch keinerlei Vorkenntnisse oder Erfahrungen in diesem Bereich? Kein Problem! In regelmäßigen Abständen finden Fachvorträge und Workshops statt. Wann welches Event stattfindet, können Sie dem Kalender entnehmen.

Ich freue mich auf Ihren Besuch in der DDR in Duisburg-Rheinhausen.

bio: @geozachct
New to 3D printing
http://daid.mine.nu/

Everybody has his own vision of 3D printed objects. I found one for myself, where I would like to stick to following rules as much as possible, when creating designs:

  • No need for support material, because it is usually a hell of work to remove it afterwards
  • Lightweight designs with ribs and holes, where it is possible to place them (and use them as design element)
  • 3D printed materials only, because I believe that 100% 3D printed, working objects and mechanisms are achievable (yet I may to consider some basic elements in future like screws and nuts, since they can be found anywhere in the world)

All of that should lead to cheap, fast and material efficient production of models.

bio: Photographer / Product Design

I'm very new to 3D Printing & 3D Design.

Getting to grips with the basics before i submit any designs/prints.

I want to make things of beauty, things of function, things of convenience, things of fun. Toys, tools, tokens.

I seem to be uploading about half of my designs. the rest are too simple or too specialized. I probably should upload some of my test parts too.

Typical characteristics of my parts:

  • Minimalistic, to reduce build time and material use without sacrificing strength
  • No need for support structure or built in supports
  • Most parts are parametric and include tolerance

I'm not interested in being paid for my parts here. Instead, leave feedback! Tell me what you like about the part, what you don't like, post pictures and makes or somehow tell me you made one. Let me know if you're using it for something interesting. If it's a parametric part, let me know if you tried changing the parameters for a specific use.

Born in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, Damon completed a Bachelor of Fine Arts from Oberlin College in 1995 and a Master of Science from Carnegie Mellon in 2002.
His accolades include a Carnegie Mellon Graduate Research Grant, the Model to Monument fellowship from the Art Students League of New York, a U.S. Patent for a mobile computer vision system, and features in New York Magazine, Gothamist, and Time Out New York.

Spanning the mediums of drawing, printmaking, ceramics, videography, photography, light, electronics, and metal, Damon’s work has been exhibited in galleries across Ohio, Illinois, Pennsylvania, and New York.

I have a Hub at www.3dhubs.com where you can request .stl files to be printed by me. Its a user friendly drag and drop type setup that allows you to easily request a quote to have just about any of these amazing objects printed and shipped for you. This service is targeted towards those who do not currently have the pleasure of owning their own 3d printer of course. No hassle, money back guarantee through 3dhubs customer support will guarantee that you will be happy with your printing request. You pay them, I print and ship, then they pay me upon receipt of the print. My Hub is Named "3DiT" after my locally operated 3d printing company here in Marietta, Ga.
